Meteo Radar

This document should be considered as a readme to familiarize with the vertical profile (vp) postgresql database content. This platform stores vertical profiles, calculated with the bioRad algorithm (ref) and stored in the file format hdf5, in a classic relational database. The rational behind this database is to provide a fast service to calculate derived measures from the vertical profiles. Because vertical profiles often need to be accessed in bulk, the current storage approach (hierarchical file system) does not allow quick processing. With a relational database processing of vertical profiles has been proven to be much more efficient. Below we first discuss the content of the database (schemas, tables), followed by practical examples on the usage in PostgreSQL and R.

1. The Database

The database consists out of several tables that are linked (related) to each other by matching fields (keys). Tables are stored in schemas. Below we discuss first the different schemas, then the main tables and finally the views that make this database.

1.1. SCHEMAS

A database is generally organised in different schemas. In this database we differentiate schemas based on their specific purpose. Different schemas may have different access properties and priviliges. We distinguish six different schemas (Figure 1; main, lu_tables, temp, tools, public and mayday) and discuss them in order of relevance for the user.

Figure 1. Screenshot of schemas in the postgresql database

1.1.1. main

The schema main is where the main tables are stored. The data model of the database will be described in more detail below.

1.1.2. lu_tables

The schema lu_tables is where the look up tables (lu_tables) are stored. These tables store the list and the description of codes referenced by other tables in the database.

1.1.3. temp

The schema temp is the work environment for any collaborator where tables can be stored temporarily. This folder will be emptied the first of every month. It is intended to keep this folder organized, so please use a relevant alias that allows to identify who generated the table (e.g., jdg_tablename).

1.1.4. tools

The schema tools will store useful tools and functions developed to facilitate the use of the database. Currently there are no tools yet available, but will be developed on demand.

1.1.5. public

The schema public should remain empty. In the public schema you can find a table with a list of projection systems (spatial_ref_sys) as generated by the POSTGIS extension. It also stores all functions available in the postgresql database.

1.1.6. mayday

The schema mayday will store error shooting when there is an issue with the database. This is only relevant for the data manager.

1.2. TABLES

This part describes the main tables of the database essential for the user. As mentioned important tables are stored in the schema main. This schema contains five tables of which two (radar_odim, radar_sensor) are related to the radar and three (vp_file, vp_data, vp_settings) to the generated vertical profiles and the associated algorithm that was used.

Figure 2. Screenshot of tables in the main schema in the postgresql database

1.2.1. radar_odim

The name and place of the radar station, the list is based on several sources, with as main source https://github.com/enram/globam-dmp/blob/master/data/OPERA_RADARS_DB.json. Following columns are included:

  • radar_odim_id Unique identifier for the radar station in db.
  • opera_radar_number Unique identifier as defined in the opera json file.
  • odim_code OPERA Data Information Model (ODIM) standard code for the radar (first two letters represent the country and the last three letters the location).
  • wmo_code World Meteorological Organization (WMO) code.
  • location_name Full name of the location of the radar.
  • country_code Official two letter abbreviation of the country where the radar is located.
  • status Whether the radar is active (TRUE) or inactive (FALSE) as from 2019-10-23.
  • vp_in_db Number of vps imported in the database for that radar location.

1.2.2. radar_sensor

Sensor specific information.

  • radar_sensor_id unique identifier for the settings (i.e., position, height,) at a radar location.
    • radar_odim_id corresponding radar location.
    • latitude Latitude position of the radar antenna (degrees), normalized to the WGS-84 reference ellipsoid and datum. Fractions of a degree are given in decimal notation.
    • longitude Longitude position of the radar antenna (degrees), normalized to the WGS-84 reference ellipsoid and datum. Fractions of a degree are given in decimal notation.
    • geom Geometry based on the longitude and latitude of the radar antenna.
    • height Height of the centre of the antenna in meters above sea level.
    • levels Number of points in the profile.
    • interval Vertical distance (m) between height intervals, or 0.0 if variable..
    • max_height Maximum height in meters above mean sea level.
    • min_height Minimum height in meters above mean sea level.
    • beam_width The radars half-power beamwidth (degrees).

1.2.3. vp_file

Vertical profile file names and related timestamps generated by pvol2bird.

  • vp_file_id unique identifier of the vpfile.
    • vp_time the actual timestamp of the vpfile.
    • start_time Start time of the data in the vp file.
    • end_time End time of the data in the vp file.
    • radar_sensor_id link to the radar sensor from which the raw radar data originates to generate the vp file.
    • vp_settings_id link to the settings of the bird2vol algorithm.
    • vp_file_original_name the original name of the vp_file.

1.2.4. vp_data

Data generated by pvol2bird.

  • vp_data_id unique identifier for each data point.
    • vp_file_id vp file unique id.
    • ff Mean horizontal wind velocity [m/s].
    • dbz Bird reflectivity factor.
    • dens Volume bird density [birds/km^3].
    • u Speed component west to east [m/s].
    • v Speed component north to south [m/s].
    • gap Angular data gap detected [1=yes, 0=no].
    • w Vertical velocity [positive upwards, m/s].
    • n_dbz Number of points bird density estimate (dbz,eta,dens).
    • dd Horizontal ground speed direction of animal movement - derived from radial velocity [degrees, clockwise from north].
    • n number of points VVP bird velocity analysis (u,v,w,ff,dd).
    • dbzh Logged horizontally-polarized (corrected) reflectivity factor.
    • hght Height above mean sea level [m].
    • n_dbz_all Number of points total reflectivity estimate.
    • eta Bird reflectivity [cm2/km3] - linear reflectivity-derived estimate.
    • sd_vvp VVP radial velocity standard deviation [m/s] derived from radial velocity. VVP = Volume Velocitty Profiling.
    • n_all Number of points VVP st.dev estimate.

1.2.5. vp_settings

Settings of the pvol2bird algorithm as stored in the hdf5 files.

  • vp_settings_id unique identifier for settings.
    • version h5 version.
    • task_args original task_args string.
    • vcp Volume Coverage Pattern.
    • comment if comments are added.
    • azimmax the maximum azimuth [degrees] used for constructing the bird density profile.
    • azimmin the minimum azimuth [degrees] used for constructing the bird density profile.
    • nlayers the number of layers in an altitude profile.
    • rangemax Maximum range at which data is used when generating bird density profile (km).
    • rangemin Minimum range at which data is used when generating bird density profile (km).
    • elevmax the maximum scan elevation [degrees] used for constructing the bird density profile.
    • elevmin the minimum scan elevation [degrees] used for constructing the bird density profile.
    • radarwavelength the wavelength [cm] of the radar.
    • usecluttermap whether a static clutter map is used.
    • cluttermap Filename of clutter map.
    • fitvrad Whether or not to fit a model to the observed vrad.
    • exportbirdprofileasjsonvar Whether to export bird profile as JSON.
    • minnyquist Minimum Nyquist velocity, scans with Nyquist velocity below this threshold are ignored.
    • maxnyquistdealias Scans with Nyquist velocity higher than this threshold are not dealiased.
    • birdradarcrosssection Bird radar cross section [cm^2].
    • stddevminbird VVP Radial velocity standard deviation threshold.
    • celletamin Minimum mean reflectivity [cm2/km3] for cells containing birds.
    • etamax Maximum reflectivity [cm2/km3] for gates containing birds.
    • dbztype reflectivity quantity to use, one of DBZH, DBZV, TH, TV.
    • requirevrad for a range gate to contribute it should have a valid radial velocity.
    • dealiasvrad TRUE if data has been dealiased, FALSE if not.
    • dualpol whether to use dual-pol moments for filtering meteorological echoes.
    • singlepol whether to use single-pol moments for filtering meteorological echoes.
    • rhohvthresmin correlation coefficients higher than this threshold will be classified as precipitation.

Figure 3. Meteo Radar Data Model

1.3. VIEWS

A view is the result set of a stored query on the data. This database includes seven views which are stored in the main schema, of which two give a summary of the vp files at different levels of detail, four calculate integrated profiles binned over different time intervals and one reconstructs the original file names as stored in the original S3-bucket.

1.3.1. Integrated profile

Integrated profiles were calculated using the same algorithms as available in bioRad. Some integrated profile variables were not included because of mismatched between original and postgresql calculation. Four views are available, binned over different temporal intervals:

  • integrate_profile
    • integrate_profile15min
    • integrate_profile30min
    • integrate_profile60min

1.3.2. Summaries vp files

Two views provide a summary of the vertical profiles per odim code at different levels.

  • vp_dayodyrmd Number of files for each day (columns) per odim code-year-month (rows).
    • vp_month_od Number of files for each month (columns) per odim code (rows).

1.3.3. Source files

  • source_files Original pvol and vp path names as stored in the S3-bucket.

2. Tutorials

2.1. DATABASE CONNECTION PARAMETERS

To access the database, whether it is from the psql console, through a database graphical user interface (e.g., pgadmin, dbeaver) or through another client software (e.g., R, matlab, qgis), connection always requires a minimum set of parameters:

  • host ibedb.science.uva.nl
    • port 5432
    • database meteo_radar
    • username
    • password

How the arguments are named will depend from the software.

2.2. POSTGRESQL

In this section a couple of examples are provided on how to use different SQL statements in this database, including FROM, WHERE, COUNT and JOIN. Next a couple of different solutions are given for the same problems. To conclude examples are given on how to query VIEWS.

2.2.1. FROM

Access the main tables in the database.
SELECT * FROM main.radar_odim;

SELECT * FROM main.radar_sensor;

SELECT * FROM main.vp_file;

SELECT * FROM main.vp_data;

SELECT * FROM main.vp_settings;

SELECT * FROM lu_tables.countries;

2.2.2. WHERE

Select a single odim from the radar_odim table
SELECT * 
FROM main.radar_odim 
WHERE odim_code = 'nldhr';
Select multiple odim codes from the radar_odim table (IN)
SELECT * 
FROM main.radar_odim 
WHERE odim_code in ('nldhr','bewir');
Select all odim codes except some from the radar_odim table (NOT IN).
SELECT * 
FROM main.radar_odim 
WHERE odim_code not in ('nldhr','bewir')
Select vp_files between two timestamps (BETWEEN AND)
SELECT *
FROM main.vp_file 
WHERE vp_time between '2018-02-15 00:00:00' and '2018-03-15 23:59:59';
Select vp_files between two timestamps (BETWEEN AND)
SELECT *
FROM main.vp_file 
WHERE vp_time between '2018-02-15 00:00:00' and '2018-03-15 23:59:59';
Select vp_files for February (EXTRACT)
SELECT *
FROM main.vp_file 
WHERE extract(month FROM vp_time) in (2);
Select vp_files for February at 18h (EXTRACT)
SELECT *
FROM main.vp_file 
WHERE extract(hour FROM vp_time) in (18) & extract(month FROM vp_time) in (18);
Add the month and hour as a column (EXTRACT)
SELECT *, extract(month FROM vp_time) monthx, extract(month FROM vp_time) timex
FROM main.vp_file 
LIMIT 5;
Shortcut to odim code from the vp_file table (LIKE, LEFT).

The odim code is also stored in the column vp_file_original_name. You can use this field as a shortcut to know the odim code for a radar.

-- Method 1 
SELECT * 
FROM main.vp_file 
WHERE vp_file_original_name like ('nldhl%');

-- Method 2
SELECT * 
FROM main.vp_file 
WHERE left(vp_file_original_name,5) in ('nldhl', 'nldbl');

2.2.3. COUNT

Count how many records are in the radar_odim table (COUNT).
SELECT count(*) records_total
FROM main.radar_odim
Count how many records have no odim code in the radar_odim table (COUNT).
SELECT count(*) records_with_odim_code
FROM main.radar_odim 
WHERE odim_code is not null
Count how many records have an odim code in the radar_odim table (COUNT).
SELECT count(*) records_without_odim_code
FROM main.radar_odim 
WHERE odim_code is null
Count proportion of records that have an odim code in the radar_odim table (COUNT).
-- Because count returns standard an integer you need to specify that it needs to be a double precision. 
-- Otherwise 0 is returned when calculating the propotion. 
SELECT count(*)::double precision /(SELECT count(*) FROM main.radar_odim) proportion
FROM main.radar_odim 
WHERE odim_code is not null
Count how many of the odim codes have data in the db (COUNT).
SELECT count(*) 
FROM main.radar_odim 
WHERE vp_in_db != 0;
Count how many vp files are in the db per month (COUNT).
SELECT extract(month from start_time) monthx, count(*) 
FROM main.vp_file 
GROUP BY extract(month from start_time);
Count how many altitude bins are there in each file (COUNT).
SELECT count(*), vp_file_id 
FROM main.vp_data
GROUP BY vp_file_id;
Are there differences in number of altitude bins between files (DISTINCT)?
SELECT DISTINCT count(*)
FROM main.vp_data
GROUP BY vp_file_id;
Check whether there are radar_odim_ids with changing sensor values (COUNT).
SELECT count(*), radar_odim_id 
FROM main.radar_sensor 
GROUP BY radar_odim_id
HAVING count(*) > 1;
Check which odim_code has changing sensor values (COUNT, JOIN).
SELECT count(*), odim_code 
FROM main.radar_odim JOIN main.radar_sensor USING (radar_odim_id) 
GROUP BY odim_code
HAVING count(*) > 1;

2.3.4. JOIN

plot vp_data including variables stored in different tables (JOIN including most tables)
SELECT vp_time, start_time, end_time, odim_code, radar_sensor_id, country_code, longitude, latitude, vp_data.*
FROM main.vp_data  
JOIN main.vp_file USING (vp_file_id) 
JOIN main.radar_sensor USING (radar_sensor_id) 
JOIN main.radar_odim USING (radar_odim_id)
WHERE odim_code = 'nldhl';

2.3.5. MULTIPLE SOLUTIONS

Often the same questions can be answered with different queries. One approach might be more efficient than another. Here are some examples on different ways to query the same question.

Count how many vp files are in the db per odim.
-- Method 1: with count
SELECT radar_odim_id, count(*) 
FROM main.vp_file   
JOIN main.radar_sensor USING (radar_sensor_id)  
GROUP BY radar_odim_id;

-- Method 3: with count using the vp_file table
SELECT left(vp_file_original_name,5) odim_code, count(*) 
FROM main.vp_file 
GROUP BY odim_code;

-- Method 2: using the record vp_in_db
SELECT odim_code, vp_in_db 
FROM main.radar_odim 
WHERE vp_in_db != 0;
Count how many vp files are in the db for a country.
-- Method 1: by summing the number of vp_in_db per country code
SELECT country_code, sum(vp_in_db) 
FROM main.radar_odim 
WHERE vp_in_db != 0 
GROUP BY country_code;

-- Method 2: count and join
SELECT country_code, count(*) 
FROM main.vp_file   
JOIN main.radar_sensor USING (radar_sensor_id)
JOIN main.radar_odim USING (radar_odim_id)
GROUP BY country_code;

-- Method 3: extract the country code from the vp_file_original_name and count
SELECT left(vp_file_original_name,2) country_code, count(*) 
FROM main.vp_file 
GROUP BY country_code;
Count how many vp files are in the db per month per odim.
-- Method 1
SELECT radar_odim_id, extract(month from start_time) monthx, count(*) 
FROM main.vp_file   
JOIN main.radar_sensor USING (radar_sensor_id)  
GROUP BY radar_odim_id, extract(month from start_time);

-- Method 2
SELECT left(vp_file_original_name,5) odim_code, extract(month from start_time) monthx, count(*) 
FROM main.vp_file 
GROUP BY odim_code, extract(month from start_time);
What is the odim_code_id of the files that have less than 20 bins?
-- Methods 1 
SELECT DISTINCT radar_odim_id FROM 
  (
  SELECT count(*), vp_file_id 
  FROM main.vp_data 
  GROUP BY vp_file_id 
  HAVING count(*) <= 20
  ) x
JOIN main.vp_file using (vp_file_id) 
JOIN main.radar_sensor USING (radar_sensor_id);

-- Methods 2
SELECT DISTINCT left(vp_file_original_name,5) odim_code, count FROM 
  (
  SELECT count(*), vp_file_id 
  FROM main.vp_data 
  GROUP BY vp_file_id 
  HAVING count(*) <= 20
  ) x
JOIN main.vp_file using (vp_file_id);

-- Methods 3
SELECT DISTINCT count(*), left(vp_file_original_name,5) odim_code 
FROM main.vp_data JOIN main.vp_file USING (vp_file_id)
GROUP BY vp_file_id, odim_code
HAVING count(*) <= 20

2.3.6. VIEWS

-- Calculate integrated profile
SELECT * FROM main.integrate_profile;

-- Calculate integrated profiles for February
SELECT * FROM main.integrate_profile WHERE extract(month from vp_time) = 2;

-- Calculate integrated profiles from February until May
SELECT * FROM main.integrate_profile WHERE extract(month from vp_time) BETWEEN 2 and 5;

-- Calculate integrated profile only for one odim code
SELECT * FROM main.integrate_profile WHERE odim_code = 'nldhl';

2.3. R

In this section we show how to interact with the database through R. This script covers how to install the uvaRadar package http://gitlab.com/bartk/uvaradar, how to query the database, import the dataset and plot the result in R, how to use the function pg_retrieve_vp to reconstruct the original vp file in hdf5 format.

2.3.1. INSTALL UVARADAR

Download the zip file directly from https://gitlab.com/bartk/uvaradar/-/archive/master/uvaradar-master.zip

# Install uvaRadar with the downloaded file
remotes::install_local('~/Downloads/uvaradar-master.zip')

2.3.2. LOAD PACKAGES

# Load packages
library(RPostgreSQL)
library(bioRad)
library(uvaRadar)

2.3.3. CONNECT TO THE DATABASE

# Connect to the database 
con <- dbConnect("PostgreSQL", 
                 dbname="meteo_radar", 
                 host="ibedb.science.uva.nl", 
                 user='<username>', 
                 password= '<password>')

2.3.4. INTERACT WITH THE DATABASE

Example 1
# Query the database (example: mtr of bejab in February)
query <- "SELECT vp_time, odim_code, mtr, extract(month FROM vp_time) monthx 
          FROM main.integrate_profile 
          WHERE odim_Code in ('bejab') AND 
          extract(year FROM vp_time) = 2018 AND 
          extract(month FROM vp_time) = 2"
vp <- dbGetQuery(con, query)

# Plot mtr 
plot(x=vp$vp_time, 
     y=vp$mtr,

Example 2
# Plot mtr for all months in 2018
par(mfrow=c(2,6), mar=c(2,1,2,1))
vp_l<-list(data.frame())
mtri<-0
mtrmax<-0
for(i in 1:12){ 
  # extract mtr for all available months 
  query <- paste0("SELECT vp_time, odim_code, mtr, extract(month FROM vp_time) monthx 
          FROM main.integrate_profile 
          WHERE odim_Code in ('bejab') AND 
          extract(year FROM vp_time) = 2018 AND 
          extract(month FROM vp_time) = ",i)
  vp <- dbGetQuery(con, query)
  
  # Plot mtr each month in separate panel
  if(nrow(vp) == 0){
  plot(x=0:1,y=0:1,col='white', xlab = NA, ylab=NA,axes=FALSE)
  } else {
  # plot mtr 
  plot(x=vp$vp_time, 
       y=vp$mtr, 
       type='l',
       main=paste0('mtr ',unique(vp$odim_code),' month ', unique(vp$monthx)),
       xlab=NA, ylab=NA)
  }
  # calculate the maximum mtr value 
  if(i == 1){if(nrow(vp)==0){mtrmax <- 0} else {mtrmax <- max(vp$mtr)}}
  if(i != 1){if(nrow(vp)==0){mtri <- 0} else { mtri <- max(vp$mtr)}}
  
  if(mtri > mtrmax){mtrmax <- mtri}
  
  vp_l[[i]] <- vp
}

# Query the database (example: mtr of bejab in February)

leaflet(radar) %>% 
  addTiles(urlTemplate="http://server.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/World_Imagery/MapServer/tile/{z}/{y}/{x}") %>% 
  addCircles(data=radar, color='red', radius = (radar$vp_in_db/sum(radar$vp_in_db))*100000, popup = ~as.character(radar$odim_code))

2.3.6. USING THE FUNCTION PG_RETRIEVE_VP

#  This function allows to reconstruct a vp. There is an option to  #
#  simplify the vp (vp_complete=TRUE) which loads vps much faster.  #
#  The function allows to filter the database on odim_code, time    #
#  and vp_file_id. It is also possible to specify your own query    #
#  This function is available in the uvaRadar package.              #

#  SELECT BY TIME INTERVAL
data1b <- pg_retrieve_vp(conn=con, 
                         time_interval = c('2018-02-01','2018-02-02'),
                         vp_complete=FALSE)
data1a <- pg_retrieve_vp(conn=con, 
                         time_interval = c('2018-02-01','2018-02-02'))

# SELECT BY ODIM AND TIME INTERVAL
data2b <- pg_retrieve_vp(conn=con, 
                         odim_code = 'bejab', 
                         time_interval = c('2018-02-01','2018-02-02'),
                         vp_complete=FALSE)
data2a <- pg_retrieve_vp(conn=con, odim_code = 'bejab', 
                         time_interval = c('2018-02-01','2018-02-02'))

# SELECT BY ODIM CODE
data3b <- pg_retrieve_vp(conn=con, 
                         odim_code = 'bejab',
                         vp_complete=FALSE) 
data3a <- pg_retrieve_vp(conn=con, 
                         odim_code = 'bejab') # slow!

# SELECT BY VP_FILE_ID
data4b <- pg_retrieve_vp(conn=con, 
                         vp_file_id = 1:100,
                         vp_complete=FALSE)
data4a <- pg_retrieve_vp(conn=con, 
                         vp_file_id = 1:100)

# RANDOM SAMPLE OF 1000 VPs
sql <- glue::glue_sql("SELECT vp_data.ff,vp_data.dbz,vp_data.dens,vp_data.u,vp_data.v,gap,w, n_dbz,vp_data.dd,n,dbzh,vp_data.hght,n_dbz_all,eta,sd_vvp,n_all,interval, left(vp_file_original_name,5) odim, vp_time, vp_file_id FROM main.vp_data JOIN main.vp_file USING (vp_file_id) JOIN main.radar_sensor USING (radar_sensor_id) ORDER BY random() LIMIT 1000",.con=conn)
data5 <- pg_retrieve_vp(conn=con, 
                        query=sql, 
                        vp_complete = FALSE)

# calculate integrate_profiles
vp_int1b <- do.call(rbind.data.frame,lapply(data1b, function(x) integrate_profile(x)))
vp_int1a <- do.call(rbind.data.frame,lapply(data1a, function(x) integrate_profile(x)))

vp_int2b <- do.call(rbind.data.frame,lapply(data2b, function(x) integrate_profile(x)))
vp_int2a <- do.call(rbind.data.frame,lapply(data2a, function(x) integrate_profile(x)))

vp_int3b <- do.call(rbind.data.frame,lapply(data3b, function(x) integrate_profile(x)))
vp_int3a <- do.call(rbind.data.frame,lapply(data3a, function(x) integrate_profile(x)))
